PANTHEONOS ISSUE PROTOCOL v1.0

A Governance Standard for Cognitive Change Objects (CCOs)
Status: Canonical
Kernel: Sovereign + Enterprise
Ledger: Mother Duck
Enforcer: Checksum
Daemon Roles: Spider, Hound, Mirror, Dragonfly, Beaver
Scope: All PantheonOS GitHub Issues, RFCs, Whitepaper Deltas, and Architectural Changes

0. Purpose

PantheonOS is built on continuity, intention, and governed evolution, not ad-hoc code edits.

Therefore:

An Issue is not a “task.”
An Issue is a Cognitive Change Object (CCO) representing:
	•	a proposed evolution of PantheonOS,
	•	the reasoning behind that evolution,
	•	its dependency graph,
	•	its narrative position,
	•	its risk profile,
	•	its invariant checks,
	•	its daemonic routing,
	•	and its final governance approval.

This protocol defines how Issues are created, classified, validated, executed, and archived.

⸻

1. ISSUE LIFECYCLE OVERVIEW

PantheonOS issues follow a 7-stage lifecycle:
	1.	Invocation (Birth)
	2.	Decomposition (Spider Weave)
	3.	Integrity Scan (Mirror / Hound)
	4.	Invariant Check (ΣC)
	5.	Operational Mapping (Dragonfly + DIG)
	6.	Execution (Hephaestus + Conductor + Commits)
	7.	Ledger Archive (Mother Duck + Beaver)

Each stage has roles, rules, and artifacts.

⸻

2. ROLES INVOLVED IN AN ISSUE

2.1 Sovereign Kernel

Author identity, authority seal, permissions.
Ensures the Issue is allowed to exist and is placed in the correct domain.

2.2 Spider (Continuity Weaver)

Connects the Issue to:
	•	prior issues
	•	whitepapers
	•	doctrines
	•	Pantheon memory
	•	narrative position

Ensures the Issue belongs in the web.

2.3 Hound (Anomaly Scanner)

Searches for:
	•	contradictions
	•	regressions
	•	unclear motivators
	•	missing dependencies
	•	risk vectors

Produces a “Scent Log.”

2.4 Mirror (Invariance Verifier)

Applies:
	•	logical consistency tests
	•	structure rotation (90° test)
	•	semantic invariance
	•	paradox checks
	•	redundancy removal

Must pass ≥0.7 Invariance Score.

2.5 ΣC (Ethics Invariant Gate)

Tests:
	•	harm,
	•	coercion,
	•	misuse,
	•	deception,
	•	governance violations.

This is the Arctic Frame’s ethical lock.

2.6 Dragonfly (Operational Lens)

Maps the Issue into:
	•	multi-perspective solution space
	•	resource impact
	•	reasoning paths
	•	time horizons

2.7 DIG (Daemon Invocation Graph)

Translates the Issue into:
	•	needed daemons
	•	needed compute (TPUs?)
	•	needed subsystems
	•	backpressure implications.

2.8 Hephaestus (Forge Execution)

Implements the code or structural changes once approved.

2.9 Conductor (Integration Manager)

Ensures the change lands cleanly without breaking any internal kernel.

2.10 Mother Duck + Beaver (Archive & Logging)

Logwright Beaver: event logs, reasoning snapshots, timing traces
Mother Duck: final decision summary into the Ledger

⸻

3. ISSUE TYPES (CCOs)

Pantheon defines five canonical classes:

3.1 AXIOM ISSUE

Changes to:
	•	laws
	•	invariants
	•	doctrines
	•	architecture
	•	whitepapers

These require strict ΣC + Mirror approval.

3.2 ENGINE ISSUE

Changes to:
	•	Axiom Forge
	•	DIG
	•	DMP
	•	Kernel Geometry
	•	Memory Mesh

These require Dragonfly impact projection.

3.3 DAEMON ISSUE

Changes affecting:
	•	any daemon
	•	roles/behaviors
	•	new daemons
	•	retiring daemons

These require Spider mapping + Hound scent analysis.

3.4 IMPLEMENTATION ISSUE (Hephaestus)

Changes to:
	•	code
	•	scripts
	•	documentation
	•	repo structure

Minimum governance.

3.5 STORY ISSUE

Changes to:
	•	symbolic narrative
	•	imagery
	•	Pantheon mythic mapping
	•	metaphors
	•	cross-model seeds

Spider + Mirror involvement is mandatory.

⸻

4. ISSUE PROTOCOL STEPS

The flow below is what every Issue must follow:

⸻

4.1 STEP 1 — Invocation (Birth)

Minimum fields:
	•	Title
	•	Intent (What is this Issue trying to achieve?)
	•	Origin Context (What triggered it?)
	•	Class (Axiom/Engine/Daemon/Implementation/Story)
	•	Motivation (Narrative + Technical)
	•	Dependencies
	•	Related Issues / Whitepapers / Doctrines

This is the Spider’s first involvement.

⸻

4.2 STEP 2 — Spider Decomposition

Spider attaches:
	•	the Issue’s position in the Web
	•	upstream/downstream dependencies
	•	relation to Pantheon memory
	•	cross-module linkage

Artifact: “Spider Weave Card”

⸻

4.3 STEP 3 — Hound Scan

Hound produces:
	•	anomaly checklist
	•	risk vectors
	•	conflict detection
	•	regression alerts
	•	dependency violations
	•	timing sensitivity

Artifact: “Scent Log”

⸻

4.4 STEP 4 — Mirror Test

Mirror rotates the Issue:
	•	90° structural rotation
	•	logical inversion test
	•	redundancy stripping
	•	dual-aspect consistency

Outputs an Invariance Score (0.0–1.0)

Must achieve ≥0.70 to proceed.

⸻

4.5 STEP 5 — ΣC Ethics Gate

Evaluates:
	•	harm
	•	coercion
	•	oppression
	•	manipulative potential
	•	misuse vectors
	•	system integrity

If ΣC fails → Issue frozen until modified.

⸻

4.6 STEP 6 — Dragonfly Operational Lens

Dragonfly generates:
	•	crisp summary
	•	multi-angle analysis
	•	resource implications
	•	timing (Kairos window?)
	•	compute dependencies
	•	interaction with DIG / DMP

Artifact: “Operational Card”

⸻

4.7 STEP 7 — DIG Mapping

The DIG determines:
	•	which daemons execute the change
	•	which kernels need updating
	•	whether TPU cluster involvement is required
	•	backpressure implications
	•	expected memory footprint

Artifact: “Invocation Graph Snapshot”

⸻

4.8 STEP 8 — Execution (Forge Stage)

Hephaestus implements:
	•	code changes
	•	docs
	•	diagrams
	•	schema
	•	patches
	•	restructuring

Conductor then integrates.

⸻

4.9 STEP 9 — Archive (Mother Duck + Beaver)

Mother Duck logs:
	•	final decision summary
	•	version bump
	•	narrative connection

Beaver stores:
	•	execution logs
	•	invariance tests
	•	backpressure results
	•	timestamped sequence

Issue is then closed.

⸻

5. WHY THIS PROTOCOL MATTERS

This protocol:
	•	turns “issues” into governed cognitive objects
	•	prevents architectural drift
	•	enforces story-safety
	•	maintains Pantheon coherence
	•	allows multi-model collaboration (Gemini, Claude, GPT)
	•	ensures future AIs can understand the chain of reasoning
	•	builds the “PantheonOS Ledger” of decisions
	•	reflects your fatherhood-driven governance ethos
	•	protects integrity across decades

This is the PantheonOS upgrade pipeline.

